            <pb n="4" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k"><choice><sic>Baeutiful</sic><corr type="editorial">Beautiful</corr></choice> Extract.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;We possess a<lb break="yes"/>genuine fragment which Cicero has pre-<lb
                        break="no"/>served to us from a lost work of Aristotle.<lb break="yes"/>It
                    runs thus; &#x201C;if there were beings who<lb break="yes"/>lived in the depths
                    of the earth, in dwell-<lb break="no"/>ings adorned with statues and
                        painting,<lb break="yes"/>and everything which is possessed in rich<lb
                        break="yes"/>abundance by those whom we esteem<lb break="yes"/>fortunate,
                    and if these beings could re-<lb break="no"/>ceive tidings of the power and
                    might of<lb break="yes"/>the Gods, and could then emerge from<lb break="yes"
                    />their hidden dwellings through the open<lb break="yes"/>fissures of the earth,
                    to the places which<lb break="yes"/>we inhabit; if they could suddenly be-<lb
                        break="no"/>hold the earth, and the sea, and the vault<lb break="yes"/>of
                    heaven, could recognize the expanse<lb break="yes"/>of the cloudy firmament and
                    the might<lb break="yes"/>of the winds of heaven, and admire the<lb break="yes"
                    />sun in its majesty, beauty, and radiant<lb break="yes"/>effulgence; and,
                    lastly, when night veiled<lb break="yes"/>the earth in darkness, they could
                        behold<lb break="yes"/>the starry heavens, the changing moon,<lb break="yes"
                    />and the stars rising and setting in the<lb break="yes"/>unvarying course
                    ordained from eterni-<lb break="no"/>ty; they would surely exclaim, there are<lb
                        break="yes"/>Gods, and such great things must be the<lb break="yes"/>work of
                    their hands.&#x201D;</p>
                <lb break="yes"/>
                <p>It has been justly observed, that this<lb break="yes"/>passage is alone
                    sufficient to corroborate<lb break="yes"/>Cicero&#x2019;s opinion of &#x201C;the
                    golden flow of<lb break="yes"/>Aristotle&#x2019;s eloquence,&#x201D; and that
                    his works<lb break="yes"/>are pervaded by something of the inspir-<lb break="no"
                    />ed force of Plato&#x2019;s genius. Such a testi-<lb break="no"/>mony to the
                    existence of the heavenly<lb break="yes"/>powers, drawn from the beauty and
                        stu-<lb break="no"/>pendous greatness of the works of crea-<lb break="no"
                    />tion, is rarely to be met with in the works<lb break="yes"/>of
                        antiquity.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Humboldt&#x2019;s Kosmos.</hi></p>
            </div>
